msContents.summary: This is an Italian manuscript from the third quarter of the fifteenth century, which contains Paulus Orosius' Historiae adversus paganos.

msItem.title: Historiae adversus paganos
msItem.incipit: //seros, quanto longius a remedio ueteris religionis, alienos ut merito hac scritatione claruerit regnasse mortem...
msItem.explicit: De qualitate autem opusculorum tu uideris, qui praecepisti tibi adiudicanda si edas, prete iudicata si deleas. Finis Pauli Orosii.

supportDesc.extent: ix+173+i; 290 x 212 mm bound to 306 x 220 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in ink, upper right, recto; modern foliation in pencil, lower right, recto in front flyleaves and first two folios

p.signatures: Quire and leaf signatures (e. g., a1, a2, a3...) on first five leaves of each quire

p.catchwords: Vertical catchwords in lower margin right of inner vertical bounding lines, some missing

layoutDesc.layout: Single column, written in thirty lines; double vertical and horizontal bounding lines, full length, ruled in hard point; written area: 197 x 120 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Alternating two- to three-line blue and red ink initials; text divisions and headings in red; marginalia in several contemporary hands and marginal notations throughout in a later hand
Inside front coverBookplate of Howard Lehman Goodhart
[Flyleaf 1 recto]Note in pencil on De Ricci

[Flyleaf 9 recto]In ink: "[Clerico?] Camillo Riccio A. V. et S. V. et am. A. et s.s. et u. f. r. et hoc verum est. Hic olim fuit R. Presbiteris V. H. Marcelli Ricci nunc vero mei Camilli Ricci sui nepotis et A. S."
174vIn ink: "Camilli Ricci Bellicastrensis sum," and repeatedly in a variety of hands: "nec no suorum amicorum omnium" or "nec non suorum natos amicorumne"
174vIn ink in another hand: "Non mancare con la prima commodita raguagliarlo di quanto occorre"
Inside back coverTyped description from H. P. Kraus taped in

binding.p: Twentieth-century luan plywood boards with worn leather spine

history.provenance: Produced in Italy in the third quarter of the fifteenth century; ownership inscription: "[Clerico?] Camillo Riccio A. V. et S. V. et am. A. et s.s. et u. f. r. et hoc verum est. Hic olim fuit R. Presbiteris V. H. Marcelli Ricci nunc vero mei Camilli Ricci sui nepotis et A. S."; on fol. 174v: "Camilli Ricci Bellicastrensis sum," and repeatedly in a variety of hands: "nec no suorum amicorum omnium" or "nec non suorum natos amicorumne."; below in another hand: "Non mancare con la prima commodita raguagliarlo di quanto occorre."; a draft of a letter found inside this book was written by the vicar of a parish church on behalf of Antonius Laurus, who was Bishop of Bellcastris from 1599-1609; no other provenance known; bought from H. P. Kraus (typed description taped to inside back cover) by Howard L. Goodhart in April 1949 (bookplate; his note on fol. 1 recto), and presented by him to Bryn Mawr College in March 1950
